---
import { Container, TextSection } from '@components/odyssey-theme';
import Layout from '../layouts/Page.astro';

const seo = {
	title: 'Context | NMES for Astronauts',
	description: 'Etiology and Affected Demographic of Muscle Degradation in Space',
};
---

<style>
  .icon-header {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    margin-right: 0.5rem;
    vertical-align: middle;
    color: var(--theme-primary);
  }
	img {
		max-width: 100%;
		border-radius: var(--theme-shape-radius);
	}
  .nav-button-container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }
  .nav-arrow {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    color: var(--theme-on-bg);
    opacity: 0.5;
    transition: all var(--theme-transition);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .nav-arrow:hover {
    color: var(--theme-primary);
    opacity: 1;
    transform: scale(1.1); /* Reduced scale slightly to accommodate text */
    filter: drop-shadow(0 0 5px var(--theme-primary));
  }
  .nav-arrow svg {
    width: 48px;
    height: 48px;
  }
  .nav-label {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-right: 0.5rem;
    letter-spacing: 2px;
  }
</style>

<Layout seo={seo}>
  <Container>
    <TextSection narrow>
      <h1 style="text-align: center;">The Context: Muscle Atrophy in Space</h1>
      
      <h3>Who is at Risk?</h3>
      <p>
        Every astronaut on a <strong>long-duration</strong> mission faces this challenge. Whether it's a 6-month stay on the ISS or a 3-year journey to Mars, the human body <strong>adapts</strong> to its environmentâ€”often in ways we don't want.
      </p>
      <p>
        Astronauts face a unique challenge: <strong>microgravity</strong>. On Earth, our muscles are constantly working against gravity to support our weight and move us around. In space, this load disappears.
      </p>
      <p>
        Without gravity pulling on them, muscles begin to <strong>weaken</strong> immediately. This isn't just about strength; it's about <strong>safety</strong>. A weakened crew member might struggle with emergency procedures or be unable to walk upon returning to Earth (or landing on Mars).
      </p>
      
      <h3>Why Does It Happen?</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Use it or lose it.</strong> On Earth, just standing up requires your "anti-gravity" muscles (legs and spine) to work against 1G of force. In space, that load disappears.
      </p>
      <p>
        The body, being efficient, stops maintaining muscle it doesn't need. The result? Up to <strong>30% muscle mass loss</strong> in just six months. Bones also become brittle, increasing fracture risk.
      </p>
      <div class="nav-button-container">
        <a href="/countermeasures" class="nav-arrow" aria-label="Next: The Solutions">
          <span class="nav-label">NEXT</span>
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line>
            <polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline>
          </svg>
        </a>
      </div>
    </TextSection>
  </Container>
</Layout>
